<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
MHD_send_hdr_and_body_ is passed a pointer into connection->write_buffer and a length (wb_ready) computed as connection->write_buffer_append_offset - connection->write_buffer_send_offset without a runtime check. If write_buffer_append_offset < write_buffer_send_offset (for example because of a logic bug, re‑initialisation error, or memory corruption), the unsigned subtraction will underflow producing a very large wb_ready and/or the pointer &write_buffer[write_buffer_send_offset] may be out of bounds (or write_buffer may be NULL). Any subsequent use of that pointer/length inside MHD_send_hdr_and_body_ (which is likely to call memcpy/other string.h functions) can therefore access memory beyond the referenced object. Note: the code only uses mhd_assert to document the invariant (append_offset >= send_offset), but asserts can be compiled out, so there is a feasible path to out‑of‑bounds access — this violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17.
</scenario>
